	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Congolese agriculture – does well but could do better  </h1>

			
			<h4>
												16 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In its latest Trade Policy Review (TPR) of the CEMAC countries, the WTO has characterised the Republic of Congo’s non-petroleum economic performance since 2009 as “good and encouraging”, with “sustained growth” in the agricultural sector, although this largely arises from developments in production of forestry products, where a key policy issue is how to encourage more domestic processing. </p><p>Farming faces more severe problems than the forestry and fisheries sector, and it is largely the latter that accounts for the WTO Secretariat’s favourable assessment of the economic performance of the non-petroleum part of the Congolese economy. In the agricultural sector per se, only about 2% of the estimated 10 million ha of cultivable land is actually being farmed. Most of the farms are small, “unprofitable and use rudimentary production techniques”. This has led to an exodus of population from rural areas, with the urban population “a relatively long way away from the centres of agricultural production”. According to the WTO Secretariat constraints on growth – as elsewhere in CEMAC – include “the high costs of factors of production, including access to credit; the poor state of the road network; and the weakness of support services”. </p><p>Domestic production benefits from the relatively high tariffs provided by the CEMAC common external tariff, averaging 23.6%, but the government has taken advantage of the scope for national derogations to reduce the tariff on agricultural inputs to 2% until 2016. However, some agro-processing is much more highly protected. Flour milling, for example, is protected by a quota on imports of wheat flour, and refined sugar imports are banned unless domestic production falls below national demand. Almost half of sugar production is exported to CEMAC partners and Congo has had a (relatively small) quota for preferential exports to the EU and USA (making it vulnerable to recent changes in the EU and US preferential trade regimes for sugar).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>WTO, ‘Trade Policy Review: Cameroon, Congo, Gabon, Central African Republic and Chad’, Annex 2, 29–31 July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp385_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp385_e.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Agricultural trade policy in a country like Congo, with its huge untapped potential for growing food but a current reliance on imports, must balance the need to foster domestic production with the food security needs of the urban population. This leads to the government maintaining price ceilings on sugar, wheat flour, rice and salted/smoked fish. &nbsp;</p><p>Unlike some of its CEMAC partners, Congo has avoided the common problem of undermining apparently protective tariffs on foodstuffs with equally high (or higher) rates on agricultural inputs. </p><p>The experience in the Congo illustrates the practical difficulties faced in encouraging greater domestic processing through the use of export taxes. In sectors where this has been attempted (unprocessed wood) it has proved largely ineffective, with firms simply choosing to pay the tax and continuing to export unprocessed products.</p><p>More seriously, this experience illustrates the limits of trade policy compared to ‘fundamentals’. Using identical words to those in the annex on Gabon, the WTO’s review sets out a litany of supply-side problems that need to be addressed: high costs, poor access to credit, poor roads and inadequate support services. In the Congo, as elsewhere in the CEMAC, getting to grips with these ‘fundamentals’ is the key challenge, with trade policy likely to play a limited role in the interim.</p>
		</div>
		
